{It is surprising how often one can hear the never out of fashion and typical
chess complaint: "I was so much better but then strange things happened and I
even lost the game". The frustration grows in intensity if a player misses a
good chance in making history by winning or holding against a top class
opponent.  For some reasons the main point is forgotten: we don't play alone
and the stronger the opponent, the trickier it gets. We may have had our
chances but that could be partly due to deliberate action from the other side!
Rewards come to those who dare and Caruana didn't falter when the time had
come to take risky decisions.  Repeatedly in this event, he went for the
double-edged continuation instead of settling for a safer path. And that was
no gambling but calculated danger, showing not bravery but a great deal of
practicality. Obviously, it paid off.  The next three games illustrates this
remarkable attitude, where Caruana went for unbalanced play, giving chances
but also creating chances in return. At the end of the day, the 'no pain, no
gain' crowned beautifully his 'hazardous' play.} 1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
4. e3 d5 5. h4 c6 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. Bd3 Ngf6 8. h5 Qb6 9. Rb1 Ne4 10. Bf4 Rg8 {
Black is worse but at the same the game is open: both sides can make
positional or tactical errors. And that is the whole point of Caruana's
strategy: the other side is given multiple and equally good choices but which
one to make?! Slowly but surely the position goes from good to less good to
acceptable to...you know the drill. Fabiano simply wants to keep the game
going, even if the opponent is a strong one!} 11. O-O Bf6 12. hxg6 hxg6 13. Na4
Qd8 14. c4 e6 15. Ne5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Nec5 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. b4 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Qh4
20. Rfc1 Rh8 21. Kf1 Bd7 22. Bg3 Qh1+ 23. Ke2 Qxg2 24. Rg1 Qh3 25. Rh1 Qxh1 26.
Rxh1 Rxh1 27. Qd4 g5 28. f4 g4 29. Kf2 b6 30. Kg2 Rc1 31. Bh4 c5 32. Qd2 Rxc4
33. Bf6 d4 34. Kg3 Rc3 35. Qh2 Rxe3+ 36. Kf2 g3+ 0-1

