{Fabiano had the same uncompromising attitude against the top female player,
deciding to offer an exchange for turning the game dynamic. In hindsight and
with the engine on, anyone can say "that was a bad idea". Objectively, many
moves can be considered 'bad' but over the board and in practical play
brilliancies come from errors too.} 19... Rfe7 {A nice idea to unbalance the
game with a positional exchange sacrifice, which could have been executed with
more precision, had we been machines.} ({Better was} 19... b6 $1 {followed by
the same idea as in the game, the difference being that this little pawn is
now saved, compared to what happened next.}) 20. d5 Ne5 ({Perhaps a better
alternative to give the exchange was} 20... Nd8 21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. Nh4 Nf7 23.
Ng6 Ng5 24. Nxe7+ Rxe7 {with promising compensation, given the Nxh3 and f3
threats.}) 21. Bxe5 Rxe5 22. Nxe5 Rxe5 23. Qxb7 f3 24. Qb3 ({Better was} 24.
Qb8+ Kh7 25. Qb3 fxg2 26. Ra2 Qe8 (26... Nxe4 {is not working anymore in view
of} 27. Qd3 {and that is the point of the intermediate check, to lure the
black king on the b1-h7 diagonal, where White has the pinning idea in place.})
27. Rxg2 Nxe4) 24... fxg2 25. Qf3 ({Another possible defence was} 25. Ra2 Nxe4
26. Rxg2 Nd2 27. Qb8+ Kh7 28. Rxe5 Nf3+ 29. Kf1 Nxe5 {Easy, right? Any engine,
you name it, would probably hold this but in a game I would blindly choose
Black with such a knight on e5 and the white pawns likely to fall, like the
teeth of an old person.}) 25... Qe8 26. Ra2 Nxe4 27. Rae2 Ng5 28. Qg4 {the
final mistake} ({But there's no blue sky after} 28. Qxg2 Nxh3+ 29. Kh2 Ng5 30.
Rxe5 dxe5 {where White has to make serious moves to defend, given the rather
open white king. And winter is coming...}) 28... Rxe2 29. Rxe2 Qxe2 30. Qxe2
Nxh3+ 31. Kh2 g1=Q+ 32. Kxh3 Kh7 33. Qd2 h5 34. Qxa5 Qh1+ 35. Kg3 h4+ 36. Kf4
Qh2+ 37. Kf5 Qe5+ 38. Kg4 Qg3+ 39. Kf5 h3 0-1

