{The games have ben thoroughly analyzed and for deeper lines I kindly suggest
checking the previous reports published on ChessBase. For now I only want to
make a point, the one of choice. This was the final round, which brought
Fabiano on a shared 1st place after defeating England's top player. Things
were far from being clear, especially over the board and Fabiano himself told
me he was suffering during the game but somehow got lucky.  Well, luck you can
also create with your bare hands and this is exactly what Caruana did. In this
position and given the tournament situation, many would have probably taken on
f6, which secures White a slight and pleasant edge but probably not more than
that. Instead, the no.2 in the world went for:} 20. Re1 $1 {Why not keep the
pressure and have some fun instead?! And offer Black options as well...} Qd7
21. Qb3 fxe5 22. dxe5 Rf8 23. Re3 Rg6 24. Kh1 Nd8 25. Rd1 c6 26. c4 d4 27. Qc2
Rg4 28. h3 Rgf4 29. b4 Rxf3 {Pretty for the public but less precise as Fabiano
mentioned. Ne6 would have kept the edge Black got in the last couple of moves.}
30. Rxf3 Rxf3 31. gxf3 Qxh3+ 32. Kg1 Qg3+ 33. Qg2 Qxe5 34. f4 $1 {A little
cute move which didn't pass unnoticed for the chess journalists. The idea
behind it is clear: freeing up the space for the rook.} Qxf4 35. Re1 Qf6 36.
Qg4 Nf7 {The final error which settled Black's fate, as Fabiano pointed out.
Adams missed that White can force the queen's trade, after which his position
becomes hopeless in the endgame.} (36... Kh7 {keeps the unbalanced position
balanced.}) 37. Re8+ Kh7 38. Re6 Qg5 39. Qxg5 Nxg5 40. Re7 c5 41. b5 axb5 42.
cxb5 c4 43. Kf2 c3 44. Ke2 Nh3 45. Rf7 1-0